  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight: it characterises properties of discovered failures by environmental type (showing which styles/environments produce more errors and higher neuron-coverage) and uses neuron-level coverage (KMNC/NBC) and steering-angle divergence to correlate failures with input-condition styles. However, it does not trace those failures to underlying model vulnerabilities (e.g., dataset bias, spurious features, corrupted training data, or overfitting), nor does it interpret the style vectors to explain why the model fails; mitigation or root-cause analysis is left for future work. Thus the work goes beyond merely reporting failures but stops short of linking them to underlying vulnerabilities.",
  "evidence": "Page 5, Section 3.2.1 (Testing coverage criteria): \"In this work, we employ DNN coverage criteria to measure the ability of a style vector to detect diverse erroneous behaviours.... we carefully select two fine-grained coverage metrics on the sub-neuron level ... i.e., k-multisection Neuron Coverage (KMNC) and Neuron Boundary Coverage (NBC).\" \n\nPage 6, Section 3.2.3 (Fitness function definition): \"The ability to detect diverse erroneous behaviours of a style vector is measured by the increase in the testing coverage measured by KMNC or NBC.... The ability to detect more erroneous behaviours ... is measured by the mean steering angle divergences between the original dataset of driving scenes and the newly synthesised driving scenes with that style vector.\" \n\nPage 7, Section 4.2 (Comparison with baselines - results): \"In terms of the achieved coverage, compared with Rc, TACTIC achieves higher coverage in all environmental types... In terms of the detected erroneous behaviours, compared with Rc and DeepRoad, TACTIC detects many more erroneous behaviours in all environmental types for both four error bounds.\" (see Tables 1 and 2 for per-environment counts and coverage) \n\nPage 4, Section 3 (end of workflow discussion): \"...the critical environmental conditions of TACTIC can also be used to synthesise more training examples to improve the performance of DNN-based ADSs by adversarial training (Pei et al., 2017; Tian et al., 2018), which we plan to study in future work.\" \n\nThese excerpts show the paper characterises failure patterns by environment and by coverage/activation regions (partial diagnostic insight) but does not perform analysis that links failures to underlying causes in the model or training data (no causal/root-cause analysis or feature-level attribution is presented)."
